Jeff,

Got it.  So if @RunWith and @... were @Inherited, your
problem would be solved?

Sorry for the response lag,

   David Saff

On Tue, Nov 4, 2008 at 1:20 PM, Jeff &lt;jjg@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; Hi David!
&gt;
&gt; Here. Let us say that I had test classes, Test0, Test1. Each of these
&gt; requires a backend to be configured. I&#39;d like to do something like this:
&gt;
&gt; @RunWith(Suite.class)
&gt; @...({Test0.class, Test1.class})
&gt; public abstract class MySuite{
&gt; abstract public void setBackend(Backend backend);
&gt;
&gt; @BeforeClass
&gt; public static void doSetup() throws Exception{
&gt; //... stuff to get this all pulled together and configure the tests
&gt; }
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; Then all a tester needs to do is extend the class MySuite, implement the
&gt; method and s/he gets to run their backend against my tests.
&gt;
&gt; Complicating factors are that java does not allow for annotations to be
&gt; inherited unless the @interface is created with the @Inherited
&gt; annotation, so attempts to do what is above kick back the message that
&gt; there are no tests to run or some such. At least this is my
&gt; understanding of java annotations...
&gt;
&gt; The real life example has not just a couple of test classes, but many
&gt; more that very rigorously exercise the backend. The kludge is to have
&gt; the abstract MySuite class and have the annotations cut and pasted every
&gt; time. This is bad since it will make maintainability problematic (we
&gt; have lots of different backend configurations people want to test
&gt; against). What&#39;s more several people who want to use this really don&#39;t
&gt; know that much about jUnit and we&#39;d really like it to be the case they
&gt; can write a backend then get good feedback on robustness, failure modes,
&gt; you name it.
&gt;
&gt; Is this clearer?
&gt;
&gt; Thanks in Advance!
&gt;
&gt; Jeff
&gt;
&gt; David Saff wrote:
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Jeff,
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Can you expand on what you mean by &quot;The problem is that making a suite
&gt;&gt; using annotations does not really work so well. The annotations are
&gt;&gt; not inherited.&quot;? Can you give an example of what you&#39;d like to do?
&gt;&gt; Thanks,
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; David Saff
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; On Mon, Nov 3, 2008 at 2:54 PM, Jeff &lt;jjg@...
&gt;&gt; &lt;mailto:jjg%40jqhome.net&gt;&gt; wrote:
&gt;&gt; &gt; Hi,
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; I am new to this group, so if there is a FAQ or thread that addresses
&gt;&gt; &gt; this, please direct me appropriately.
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; I wrote a comprehensive set of tests in jUnit that run under Maven. Now,
&gt;&gt; &gt; these run against a single backend and now several developers in my
&gt;&gt; &gt; group would like to use these tests against other backends to test them.
&gt;&gt; &gt; The most natural way to do this is with the test suite mechanism in
&gt;&gt; &gt; jUnit. That is to say, make up a suite that requires merely that the
&gt;&gt; &gt; backend be set and test away. Or so I thought.
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; The different backends are different projects in our group and live in
&gt;&gt; &gt; different Maven modules.
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; The problem is that making a suite using annotations does not really
&gt;&gt; &gt; work so well. The annotations are not inherited. The other solution
&gt;&gt; &gt; which is to have the developers make their own suites by annotations is
&gt;&gt; &gt; also very clunky and will probably break at some point.
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; So here is my question: Is there any way to make a test suite that is a
&gt;&gt; &gt; harness and can be reused?
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; I assume that jUnit 3.8&#39;s method of explicitly creating a suite is going
&gt;&gt; &gt; to get deprecated soon, right? So that would be a deadend. Also, are
&gt;&gt; &gt; their plans to make annotations inheritable at some point in jUnit? We
&gt;&gt; &gt; could maybe live with cutting and pasting for the short term if we knew
&gt;&gt; &gt; that this issue would get resolved at some point.
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; Thanks!
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; Jeff
